---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Our Story | Runaway Train Café — A Texas Landmark Since the 1940s">
  <Header />
  
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero-section relative h-[60vh] min-h-[450px] flex items-center justify-center overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute inset-0">
      <img 
        src="/2698530_orig.jpg" 
        alt="" 
        class="w-full h-full object-cover"
        loading="eager"
        fetchpriority="high"
      />
    </div>
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-train-brown/60 via-train-brown/70 to-train-brown/90"></div>
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
    <div class="hero-content relative z-10 text-center px-6">
      <p class="text-train-gold font-bold tracking-[0.25em] uppercase mb-4 text-sm text-shadow">A Texas Landmark</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mb-6">
        80 Years of Railroad History
      </h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        This isn't just a restaurant. It's a piece of Texas that refused to disappear.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- The Full Story -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-28 bg-train-cream">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      
      <!-- Opening -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-train-brown mb-8">
          You're sitting where travelers sat 80 years ago.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          In the 1940s, this train car was rolling through Texas, serving hot meals to passengers 
          traveling across the state. The dining car was the heart of long-distance rail travel — 
          white tablecloths, real silverware, and food cooked on board.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed">
          When the age of rail travel ended, most of these dining cars were scrapped. Not this one. 
          It found a home in Brownwood, Texas, and became something new: a place where families 
          could experience that same feeling of sitting down to a real meal in a real train car.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Photo break -->
      <div class="my-16 grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <img 
          src="/9548696_orig.jpg" 
          alt="The original ice cream counter" 
          class="rounded-2xl shadow-xl w-full"
          loading="lazy"
          width="600"
          height="400"
        />
        <img 
          src="/884524_orig.jpg" 
          alt="Vintage train car details" 
          class="rounded-2xl shadow-xl w-full"
          loading="lazy"
          width="600"
          height="400"
        />
      </div>
      
      <!-- The Experience -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-train-brown mb-8">
          Walk in. Time travel back.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The moment you step inside, you feel it. The curved ceiling. The narrow walkway between booths. 
          The windows that once showed miles of Texas prairie rolling by. We kept everything intact — 
          the original booths, the stools at the counter, the chrome fixtures.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed">
          The ice cream counter is the same one where railroad passengers once ordered malts and floats 
          between Amarillo and Houston. Your kids can sit on the same stools, spinning the way kids have 
          spun on those stools for 80 years.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Quote callout -->
      <blockquote class="my-16 bg-train-brown rounded-2xl p-10 text-center">
        <p class="text-2xl md:text-3xl text-train-cream font-semibold italic mb-6 text-shadow">
          "This isn't just a diner. It's a Texas landmark. We're just the ones lucky enough to keep it running."
        </p>
        <footer class="text-train-gold font-bold">— Kim B., Owner</footer>
      </blockquote>
      
      <!-- The Food -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-train-brown mb-8">
          The food is simple. That's the point.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Half-pound burgers, made with fresh beef we grind ourselves. Homemade soup, different every day. 
          Sandwiches built on real bread. Blue Bell ice cream, because this is Texas and there's no other choice.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          No fancy plating. No foam or drizzles. Just honest food, cooked when you order it, served by 
          people who know your name after a few visits.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed">
          Our customers' favorites haven't changed in years: the <strong>Jalapeño Bacon Cheeseburger</strong> 
          and the <strong>Mushroom Swiss</strong>. Ask for the soup and half sandwich combo — it's the 
          lunch that regulars order without looking at a menu.
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Photo break -->
      <div class="my-16">
        <img 
          src="/hamburger_orig.jpg" 
          alt="Fresh half-pound burger" 
          class="rounded-2xl shadow-xl w-full"
          loading="lazy"
          width="800"
          height="500"
        />
      </div>
      
      <!-- Small Town -->
      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-train-brown mb-8">
          Brownwood's gathering spot.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Friday nights here are loud. Families pile in after games. Tourists stop on their way through. 
          Regulars grab their usual booth. The counter fills up with people who've been coming here 
          since they were kids, now bringing their own kids.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl text-train-brown/80 leading-relaxed">
          That's what a train car diner is supposed to be — not a museum, not a themed attraction, 
          but a real place where real people eat real food. We've been doing this since the days 
          of the railroads, and we're not planning to stop.
        </p>
      </div>
      
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-20 md:py-28 bg-train-brown">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-train-cream mb-8 text-shadow">
        Come see it for yourself.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-train-cream/80 mb-10">
        3600 Stephen F. Austin Dr, Brownwood, TX 76801<br/>
        <span class="text-train-gold font-semibold">Right off Highway 377</span>
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-5 justify-center">
        <a 
          href="tel:+13256463333" 
          class="btn-primary text-xl inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-3"
        >
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path d="M2 3a1 1 0 011-1h2.153a1 1 0 01.986.836l.74 4.435a1 1 0 01-.54 1.06l-1.548.773a11.037 11.037 0 006.105 6.105l.774-1.548a1 1 0 011.059-.54l4.435.74a1 1 0 01.836.986V17a1 1 0 01-1 1h-2C7.82 18 2 12.18 2 5V3z" />
          </svg>
          (325) 646-3333
        </a>
        <a 
          href="https://maps.google.com/?q=3600+Stephen+F+Austin+Dr+Brownwood+TX+76801" 
          target="_blank"
          class="btn-secondary text-xl inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-3"
        >
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-6 w-6" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.05 4.05a7 7 0 119.9 9.9L10 18.9l-4.95-4.95a7 7 0 010-9.9zM10 11a2 2 0 100-4 2 2 0 000 4z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
          Get Directions
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  
  <Footer />
</Layout>
